WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.550
Time to put real credentials in a place

00:00:03.550 --> 00:00:04.506
forks can't reach!

00:00:04.506 --> 00:00:05.780
We'll set two secrets,

00:00:05.780 --> 00:00:08.330
deploy the app and prove it really receives

00:00:08.330 --> 00:00:08.649
them,

00:00:08.649 --> 00:00:11.198
then fork the repo and watch the fork

00:00:11.198 --> 00:00:12.473
come up empty handed.

00:00:12.473 --> 00:00:13.748
It can't even start.

00:00:14.524 --> 00:00:17.276
Most teams drop a dot env file

00:00:17.276 --> 00:00:20.027
into the repo because it's the obvious

00:00:20.027 --> 00:00:20.420
move.

00:00:20.420 --> 00:00:23.172
The problem is the fork inherits a

00:00:23.172 --> 00:00:25.137
byte-for-byte copy of the image,

00:00:25.137 --> 00:00:27.889
so your sandbox boots with the production

00:00:27.889 --> 00:00:30.640
Stripe key and starts charging real customer

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:31.033
cards.

00:00:34.310 --> 00:00:34.711
First,

00:00:34.711 --> 00:00:37.116
set a secret in env mode.

00:00:37.116 --> 00:00:39.921
The value lands as an environment variable

00:00:39.921 --> 00:00:41.124
inside the container.

00:00:41.124 --> 00:00:43.930
First writes need no ceremony — it

00:00:43.930 --> 00:00:46.735
is overwriting an existing secret that requires

00:00:46.735 --> 00:00:47.136
proof.

00:00:48.966 --> 00:00:51.526
Set. The value will land in the container as

00:00:51.526 --> 00:00:52.886
an environment variable.

00:00:56.383 --> 00:00:58.943
Now a file mode secret. File mode never

00:00:58.943 --> 00:01:02.063
puts the value in the container environment. It

00:01:02.063 --> 00:01:06.383
writes it to a file at slash run slash secrets, using

00:01:06.383 --> 00:01:08.943
Docker standard mechanism. Prefer this

00:01:08.943 --> 00:01:10.143
for anything sensitive.

00:01:12.004 --> 00:01:14.564
Set as a file. The container reads

00:01:14.564 --> 00:01:17.284
it from /run/secrets

00:01:17.764 --> 00:01:18.964
, never as an env var.

00:01:22.484 --> 00:01:25.284
Let us list what we have. Names and modes

00:01:25.284 --> 00:01:27.844
only. The list never shows values

00:01:28.164 --> 00:01:29.444
, no matter who is asking.

00:01:31.813 --> 00:01:34.773
Names and modes only. Values

00:01:34.853 --> 00:01:36.213
are never displayed.

00:01:37.151 --> 00:01:39.741
The CLI follows the GitHub Actions model:

00:01:39.741 --> 00:01:41.222
get returns a digest,

00:01:41.222 --> 00:01:42.332
never the value.

00:01:42.332 --> 00:01:44.922
If you lose track of a secret,

00:01:44.922 --> 00:01:46.033
you don't peek,

00:01:46.033 --> 00:01:46.773
you rotate,

00:01:46.773 --> 00:01:49.363
and the audit log records it as

00:01:49.363 --> 00:01:50.473
a deliberate change.

00:01:53.813 --> 00:02:00.053
Now the part that surprises people. The secret get command returns a digest, not the value

00:02:00.533 --> 00:02:03.093
. There is no flag that gives the plaintext back

00:02:03.573 --> 00:02:06.613
. That is the GitHub Actions model: write only

00:02:06.613 --> 00:02:07.333
by design.

00:02:09.277 --> 00:02:12.077
Digest, not plaintext. The CLI

00:02:12.077 --> 00:02:13.837
won't show secrets to anyone.

00:02:17.263 --> 00:02:19.823
Lost the value? Do not peek

00:02:20.143 --> 00:02:23.103
. Rotate. The rotate-secret flag skips

00:02:23.103 --> 00:02:25.743
the precondition check, and the audit log marks

00:02:25.743 --> 00:02:28.303
the change as a deliberate rotation

00:02:28.863 --> 00:02:30.863
. Loud, intentional, safe.

00:02:32.977 --> 00:02:35.697
Rotated. The audit log marks this

00:02:35.697 --> 00:02:37.137
as a deliberate replacement.

00:02:40.488 --> 00:02:43.257
Time to prove the secrets actually work.

00:02:43.257 --> 00:02:44.444
Deploy the repo.

00:02:44.444 --> 00:02:46.422
The compose file consumes both:

00:02:46.422 --> 00:02:48.399
the env value through interpolation,

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:51.168
the file value through a Docker secrets

00:02:51.168 --> 00:02:51.564
mount.

00:02:54.314 --> 00:02:55.103
Services started.

00:02:55.103 --> 00:02:57.867
Both secrets were delivered at deploy time.

00:03:01.190 --> 00:03:03.133
Did the env secret arrive?

00:03:03.133 --> 00:03:05.853
Ask the container to print the variable.

00:03:05.853 --> 00:03:07.407
There is the value:

00:03:07.407 --> 00:03:08.573
postgres dot internal.

00:03:08.573 --> 00:03:10.516
The app really got it.

00:03:12.016 --> 00:03:13.054
There's the value.

00:03:13.054 --> 00:03:14.785
The app really received it.

00:03:18.119 --> 00:03:19.489
And the file secret?

00:03:19.489 --> 00:03:22.228
Read it from slash run slash secrets inside

00:03:22.228 --> 00:03:22.913
the container.

00:03:22.913 --> 00:03:23.940
There it is,

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:24.967
the rotated value.

00:03:24.967 --> 00:03:26.679
The app reads the plaintext;

00:03:26.679 --> 00:03:29.419
it is only the tooling that refuses to

00:03:29.419 --> 00:03:30.788
show it to you.

00:03:32.038 --> 00:03:33.120
The rotated value,

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:34.562
live in the container.

00:03:34.562 --> 00:03:36.004
Write-only applies to humans,

00:03:36.004 --> 00:03:37.446
not to your app.

00:03:38.222 --> 00:03:39.582
Here's the payoff.

00:03:39.582 --> 00:03:42.301
The fork shares the parent's encrypted

00:03:42.301 --> 00:03:42.755
data,

00:03:42.755 --> 00:03:45.474
but the secret store is scoped

00:03:45.474 --> 00:03:46.381
per repo,

00:03:46.381 --> 00:03:48.647
so the fork lists empty,

00:03:48.647 --> 00:03:51.367
can't interpolate any of your production

00:03:51.367 --> 00:03:51.820
keys,

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:54.539
and can't even start the parent's

00:03:54.539 --> 00:03:54.993
compose.

00:03:58.263 --> 00:03:59.278
Now the punchline.

00:03:59.278 --> 00:04:00.969
We will fork the repo.

00:04:00.969 --> 00:04:03.674
The fork is a byte-for-byte copy of the

00:04:03.674 --> 00:04:04.689
parent encrypted image.

00:04:07.915 --> 00:04:08.739
Fork created.

00:04:08.739 --> 00:04:11.624
A byte-for-byte copy of the encrypted image.

00:04:14.911 --> 00:04:17.803
But when we list the fork secrets:

00:04:17.803 --> 00:04:18.217
empty.

00:04:18.217 --> 00:04:19.456
No Stripe key,

00:04:19.456 --> 00:04:20.696
no database password,

00:04:20.696 --> 00:04:21.936
no API token.

00:04:21.936 --> 00:04:24.828
The fork cannot pretend to be you.

00:04:24.828 --> 00:04:26.894
That is why clone production,

00:04:26.894 --> 00:04:28.547
break nothing actually works.

00:04:29.347 --> 00:04:29.750
Empty.

00:04:29.750 --> 00:04:32.171
The fork starts with no secrets,

00:04:32.171 --> 00:04:32.978
by design.

00:04:36.323 --> 00:04:37.375
One more proof.

00:04:37.375 --> 00:04:40.179
Try to start the fork with the parent

00:04:40.179 --> 00:04:40.530
compose.

00:04:40.530 --> 00:04:41.231
It fails:

00:04:41.231 --> 00:04:44.036
the bind source path for the Stripe key

00:04:44.036 --> 00:04:46.140
does not exist under the fork.

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:48.243
Production credentials never follow a fork,

00:04:48.243 --> 00:04:49.645
not even by accident.

00:04:49.645 --> 00:04:51.927
Bind source path does not exist.

00:04:51.927 --> 00:04:54.208
The missing secret blocks the start,

00:04:54.208 --> 00:04:56.490
and that failure is the feature.

00:04:57.256 --> 00:05:00.001
And that's secrets locked down where forks can't

00:05:00.001 --> 00:05:00.344
follow.

00:05:00.344 --> 00:05:02.402
See you in the next one!
